SIMPLE: sickly
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sickly
<hw>Sick"ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Sicklier</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Sickliest</adjf>.]</amorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Somewhat sick;
disposed to illness; attended with disease; <as>as, a <ex>sickly</ex>
body</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This physic but prolongs thy <qex>sickly</qex> days.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Producing, or tending to, disease; <as>as, a
<ex>sickly</ex> autumn; a <ex>sickly</ex> climate</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Cowper.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Appearing as if sick; weak; languid; pale.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The moon grows <qex>sickly</qex> at the sight of day.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nor torrid summer's <qex>sickly</qex> smile.</q>
<rj><qau>Keble.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Tending to produce nausea; sickening; <as>as, a
<ex>sickly</ex> smell; <ex>sickly</ex> sentimentality.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Diseased; ailing; infirm; weakly; unhealthy;
healthless; weak; feeble; languid; faint.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sickly</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sickly
<hw>Sick"ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a sick manner or condition;
ill.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My people <qex>sickly</qex> [with ill will] beareth our
marriage.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sickly</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Sickly
<hw>Sick"ly</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To make sick or sickly; -- with
<xex>over</xex>, and probably only in the past participle.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Sicklied</qex> o'er with the pale cast of thought.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sentiments <qex>sicklied</qex> over . . . with that cloying
heaviness into which unvaried sweetness is too apt to subside.</q>
<rj><qau>Jeffrey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sickness</ent>⟦br⟧
